{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> σκότος</b>, ὁ, <br /> more rarely <b>σκότος</b>, εος, τό (see. entry near the end), <b>darkness, gloom</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.389, 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 121.4, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 142, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to φάος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 319 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 417, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to ἡμέρα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Definitiones” 411b. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] always of the <b>darkness</b> of death, mostly in phrase τὸν δὲ σ. ὄσσε κάλυψεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4.461, +others; στυγερὸς δ᾽ ἄρα μιν σ. εἷλεν 5.47, 13.672 \">Refs</a>]; so in Trag. and Comedy texts, σκότῳ θανεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 837 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἤδη με περιβάλλει σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ph.” 1453; σ. γίγνεται 5th c.BC: Pherecrates Comicus 40 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σκότον εἶναι τεθνηκότος (i.e. Αἰσχύλου) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 643. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> of the nether world, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 130; σκότον νέμονται Τάρταρόν τε 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 72, compare “Pers.” 223; τὸν ἀεὶ κατὰ γᾶς σ. εἱμένος 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1701 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; παῖδες ἀρχαίου Σκότου[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 106; ἰὼ σ., ἐμὸν φάος [prev. author] “Aj.” 394 (Lyric poetry); γῆς σκότῳ κέκρυπται 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 62; σκότου πύλαι [prev. author] “Hec.” 1. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> the <b>darkness</b> of the womb, φυγόντα μητρόθεν σκότον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 664: _plural_, ἐν σκότοισι νηδύος τεθραμμένη [prev. author] “Eu.” 665. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> of blindness, σκότου νέφος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1313 (Lyric poetry); ὁθούνεκ᾽.. ἐν σκότῳ.. ὀψοίατο, i.e. οὐκέτι ὀψοίατο, [prev. work] 1273 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; βλέποντα νῦν μὲν ὄρθ᾽, ἔπειτα δὲ σκότον, i.e. μηδέν,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 419; σκότον δεδορκώς 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 377, compare “HF” 563. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__5.b</b></Level4> <b>dizziness, vertigo</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “ἐπιδημίαι” 5.23; σκότοι πρὸ τῶν ὀμμάτων 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 584a3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; compare σκοτόδινος, -δινιάω. <br /><Level3><b>__6</b></Level3> <i>metaphorically</i>, σκότῳ κρύπτειν hide in <b>darkness</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1396 (Lyric poetry), compare 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Frr.” 42.5, 228\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σκότον ἔχειν to be in <b>darkness, obscurity</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “N.” 7.13, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 1052.8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀπορία καὶ σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 837a; περικαλύψαι τοῖσι πράγμασι σκότον 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 1522: with Preps., διὰ σκότους ἡ ὁδός\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] it is dark and uncertain, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 2.5.9; ἐν σ. καθήμενος 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 1.83; μηδὲν ἐν σ. τεχνωμένων 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 494; κατὰ σκότον [prev. author] “Ph.” 578; ὑπὸ σκότου [prev. author] “Ant.” 692, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 1457 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 4.6.4; ὑπὸ σκότῳ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1030 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 1214. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__7</b></Level3> of a person, Μητρότιμος ὁ σ., like{ὁ σκοτεινός}, the <b>mystery-man</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Hipponax Iambographus 78 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; also, <b>darkness</b>, i.e. <b>ignorance</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 19.226 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; <b>deceit</b>, σ. καὶ ἀπάτη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 864c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__8</b></Level3> <i>plural</i>, σκότη <b>shadows</b> in a picture, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Grammaticus “fragment” 300, 10th c.AD: Suidas Legal icographus see entry {ἀπεσκοτωμένα}, 12th c.AD: Eustathius Episcopus Thessalonicensis 953.51.— 2nd c.AD: Aelius Dionysius Grammaticus “fragment” 217 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>] regarded the <i>masculine</i> as the <i>Attic dialect</i> form: the <i>neuter</i> never occurs in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], and is nowhere required by the metre in Trag., though it sometimes occurs in codices, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 831, “HF” 1159, “fragment” 534, variant in 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 40, uncertain reading in 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 6 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; it is found, however, without variant, in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 42.5 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] and <i>Attic dialect</i> Prose, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 516e, “Cra.” 418c, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.159, etc.; also in 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.121. έ, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 2.5.9, 7.4.18 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; the word is always <i>neuter</i> in LXX and “NT.”<br /><b> σκοτί-α</b>, ἡ, <br /> (σκότος) <b>darkness, gloom</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.1698, LXX (LXX.Mic.3.6, +others), “NT” (NT.Matt.10.27, +others), cf. Moer. p.354 P. \">NT+3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> in Architecture, <b>scotia, cavetto</b>, a sunken moulding, so called from <b>the dark shadow</b> it casts, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Vitruvius Scriptor de Architectura Latinus 3.5.2, 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>Σκοτιά</b>, epithet of Aphrodite in Egypt, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. author] \">Refs</a>]","strongNumber":"G4655","accentedUnicode":"σκότος","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G4639","matchingForm":"σκιά","stepTransliteration":"skia","gloss":"shadow","_zh_tw_Gloss":"影兒, 蔭","_es_Gloss":"sombra","_zh_Gloss":"影儿, 荫"},{"strongNumber":"G4652","matchingForm":"σκοτεινός","stepTransliteration":"skoteinos","gloss":"dark","_zh_tw_Gloss":"黑暗","_es_Gloss":"oscuro","_zh_Gloss":"黑暗"},{"strongNumber":"G4653","matchingForm":"σκοτία","stepTransliteration":"skotia","gloss":"darkness","_zh_tw_Gloss":"黑暗","_es_Gloss":"oscuridad","_zh_Gloss":"黑暗"},{"strongNumber":"G4654","matchingForm":"σκοτίζω","stepTransliteration":"skotizō","gloss":"to darken","_zh_tw_Gloss":"要變黑","_es_Gloss":"oscurecer","_zh_Gloss":"要变黑"},{"strongNumber":"G4656","matchingForm":"σκοτόω","stepTransliteration":"skotoō","gloss":"to darken","_zh_tw_Gloss":"黑暗","_es_Gloss":"oscurecer","_zh_Gloss":"黑暗"}],"shortDef":"darkness, 